Obtaining tidyverse packages

This lab focuses on making figures using the ggplot2 package, which is one of several tidyverse packages. To obtain ggplot2, you will need to first install the library, and then load the library for use in your current R session. The library has already been installed for you, but if you were to install it, here’s what you would do!

The command to install packages is install.packages() - you must provide package names in quotes! to this function:

install.packages("tidyverse") # install all tidyverse packages at once

This command will take several minutes to run and complete, and you may see red text going down the console - don’t worry! These are just messages indicating the stage of installation; they are not errors. You only need to run package installation ONCE within a given RStudio Cloud space (or, once on your computer). Once it has been installed, you can use the package by loading it when needed.

Once this package installation completes, you can load packages for use with the library() function (do NOT use quotes here!):

library(tidyverse)

The output from loading the tivyverse explicitly tells you a) which packages were loaded aka “attached” to the current R session (these are the core packages of the tidyverse), and b) the versions of those packages. Package functions and features sometimes changes in different versions, so it is actually very important to know which version you use for a given coding session. In this class, we will cover all of these packages except (time pending!) stringr(convenient functions for working with strings), forcats (convenient functions for working with factors), and purrr (functional programming).

Any single package can also be loaded on its own, e.g. for today you could just use the code library(ggplot2) and be able to use all of ggplot2’s functionality. Once we get more involved with the tidyverse, however, the convenience of loading all the packages at once will become very clear.

Anatomy of a plot

The philosophy behind ggplot2 is a Grammar of Graphics: decomposing aspects of a figure into the specific role each aspect plays in the structure of the figure.

Grammar of Graphics

Today, we will focus on the first three components (reading from the bottom-up!), with a couple others tossed in for fun!:

  1. Data - the actual data that will be used to create the figure
  2. Aesthetics - how will aspects of the data be mapped into the figure? These include mapped visual components like color, shape, size, etc. This further includes the grammatical category of Scales, which control how these mappings are perceived (e.g., which colors should be used when mapping data to color?).
  3. Geometrics (geoms) - what will the literal geometric shape be that represents the data? This mostly corresponds to the type of plot you will make, e.g. the geom in a boxplot is a boxplot. The geom in a histogram is a histogram. The geom of a scatterplot is points. Many geoms implicitly are related to Statistics, because sometimes data needs to be statistically transformed to get the geometry right. This will make more sense after today’s activities, I promise/hope.

The table below is very comprehensive. Don’t memorize the “Geoms” cheatsheet, please.

Aesthetics Geoms

Visualizing quantitative distributions

We will begin by making figures of quantitative distributions using the iris dataset. As always, we LOOK AT the data before beginning to understand the different variable types.

head(iris)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa

The main types of plots (geoms!) for representing distributions of quantitative data are the following (but there are others):

  1. Histograms
  2. Density plots
  3. Boxplots
  4. Violin plot (density plot meets boxplot)
  5. Strip (jitter) plots and related

The basic anatomy of building a plot with ggplot2 is to declare a plot with the function ggplot() (no 2!) and then add components to this plot with +.

## Start a plot to visualize the data frame `iris`
ggplot(iris)

As you can see, this plot (blank grey square) is..uninspiring. It has a created a blank canvas for us, but we now need to specify more information to actually get a plot.

Histograms

We will fill in this command to make a histogram of the Sepal Lengths for all flowers in the dataset. The first question to ask yourself when making any figure is, what variables go on the X-axis and Y-axis? In this case, the X-axis should show the sepal lengths, and the Y-axis should show the counts for each bin of sepal lengths. In effect, this represents a statsitical transformation of the data itself, but by specifying a histogram geom, ggplot2 will take care of this transformation magic.

Therefore, we only need to specify the X-axis data for making a histogram. This represents an AESTHETIC MAPPING: We are telling ggplot2 to take the data from Sepal.Length and map it onto the X axis of the plot. Whenever specifying a direct relationship between the DATA and a GRAPHICAL COMPONENT, we specify within aes():

## Specify the x-axis aesthetic
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length))

Now, we’re starting to get somewhere: We have an X-axis with values for Sepal.Length templated on. ggplot2 has chosen for us a reasonable range of values on the X-axis, but we will learn later how this can be modified. We just need our actual geom (how should these data be graphically represented?) which can be added to the ggplot object.

## Add in the geom
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

And voila, we have a histogram! You’ll also notice a warning (not error!) message from ggplot2 letting us know how it binned the data (30 bins along the X-axis), and suggests how we might change the binning to our liking.

## Change the binning
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1) # each bin has a range along the X-axis of 1. Much less resolution

## Change the binning.We separate lines of ggplot code for visual clarity
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.1) # each bin has a range along the X-axis of 0.1. Much more resolution

Let’s pretty-up the plot a little bit. Some visual aspects we can modify include: + The color (i.e. outline) and fill of the histogram geom itself. + The background color, aka the plot theme + The axis labels

First, let’s change the histogram colors:

## add histogram color
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "red")

And also its fill:

## add histogram color AND fill
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "red", fill = "forestgreen")

In fact, these colors were a VERY BAD CHOICE because they cannot be differentiated by many common types of colorblindness, and they are also pretty contrasting and glaring. Always strive to use eyeball- and colorblind-friendly palettes to make your figures more accessible to a broad audience!!

We can also now tweak the overall theme of the plot. These are heavily customizable, but there are also many built-in options. The default theme of theme_gray() has a gray background with a grid, among other visual components. Let’s try another one, such as theme_classic():

## add colorblind-friendly colors and a new theme
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "dodgerblue") +
  theme_classic()

Finally, let’s tweak the axis labels. By default, the name of the column plotted is used on its axis, and histogram Y-axes are given the name “count”. One way (but as we will see, NOT the only way!) to modify this is with the function labs(). Within the Grammar of Graphics, axis titles are regarded as scales.

## add x and y axis labels
ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "dodgerblue") +
  theme_classic() + 
  labs(x = "Sepal Length (cm)", 
       y = "Count")

You can also write, for axis labels, xlab("Sepal Length (cm)") + ylab("Count"). Keep coming to class for even more choices!

To save and export this plot, we can save it to a variable, and then use the function ggsave() to save it to a file.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "dodgerblue") +
  theme_classic() + 
    labs(x = "Sepal Length (cm)", 
       y = "Count") -> p  ## Assignment!

## Save the plot, stored in variable `p`
## Check out ?ggsave for more information
ggsave("iris_histogram.pdf", p) ## To make sure the plot looks ok, we have to open the file and examine its aspect ratio.

Density plots

One problem with the histograms we’ve made is that there are actually three species in the iris dataset, but our data visualization cannot help us understand the differences among species.

One way to achieve this goal is to specify a different histogram color for each species. This means the variable Species is being MAPPED onto color and/or fill. This constitutes an aesthetic because we are taking information from the data and applying a specific graphical element. We are no longer saying “make the fill the color blue” - we are saying “make the fill based on the SPECIES value”. Therefore, fill needs to be inside an aes():

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = Species))

We now have three fills and an automatically generated legend! However, the plot is very hard to read - we can’t tell where the maximum Setosa sepal length is because it is covered by the other distributions. To address this, we can specify an alpha argument, which does color opacity: 0 is completely opaque and 1 is completely translucent.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(fill = Species), alpha = 0.6) ## Alpha is NOT mapping to the data, so don't put it in aes!!

Well, that didn’t work - histograms don’t play very well with alpha. Instead, we can make a density plot which gives a smoothened histogram. The basic X/Y components are the same, but the geom is different:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = Species), alpha = 0.6)

Now we can really see the differences, and even draw conclusions! Setosa irises have the smallest sepal lengths on average, and viriginca has the largest on average. Setosa irises also have the most narrow distribution compared to versicolor and virginica.

NOTE: aes() arguments can be supplied to many different places in the ggplot command. For example, this code is effectively equivalent: ggplot(iris) + geom_density(aes(x = Sepal.Length, fill = Species), alpha = 0.6)

The colors you see are ggplot’s default color scheme, but can be modified in a variety of ways (See section “Scales” here). Color schemes are regarded as scales in the Grammar of Graphics.

One option is to create our OWN colorscheme with the function scale_fill_manual() (its color equivalent is scale_color_manual(); eventually, you will use the wrong one, and you will have to figure it out!).

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = Species), alpha = 0.6) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("blue", "pink", "yellow"))

NOTE: The automatic arrangement of setosa, versicolor, virginica is based on the factor order. In the coming weeks, we will learn how to manipulate factors to customize the ordering.

Jitter plots (strip plots)

The final type of plot we can use to visualize distributions is known as a “jitter plot” or a “strip plot”. This type of plot actually displays the individual data POINTS themselves, rather than “massaging them” into a distribution.

For example, here is a jitter plot of iris sepal lengths across species:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_jitter()

In fact, geom_jitter() is a special kind of call to geom_point() which makes POINTS! It is equivalent to geom_point(position = "jitter"). These types of plots are very useful for visualizing the data in its “rawest” form, while still being able to discern trends.

However, the three separate distributions are difficult to see, so let’s make each chunk of points more narrow with the argument width (I know this exists because I looked at the help menu for geom_jitter()! I am not clairvoyant! I looked it up! You can too!). This argument is not an aesthetic because it has no specific mapping to data - it applies to all the data equally, so we do not place it into aes().

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.05)

Now the points are too close to each other to read, so let’s try a different width value:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species, y = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.15)

Visualizing categorical distributions

We will now describe distributions of categorical data. The standard way to describe categorical distributions is by looking at the COUNTS of each category, which we can achieve with bar plots.

Let’s remind ourselves which variable(s) are categorical in iris. Seems Species is the only one..

head(iris)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
## 1          5.1         3.5          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 2          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 3          4.7         3.2          1.3         0.2  setosa
## 4          4.6         3.1          1.5         0.2  setosa
## 5          5.0         3.6          1.4         0.2  setosa
## 6          5.4         3.9          1.7         0.4  setosa

There are generally two broad ways a bar plot can come together:

  1. You tell ggplot the categorical variable to consider, and ggplot counts occurrences for you!. We accomplish this with the geom geom_bar() (which implicitly does the counting, much like geom_histogram() implicitly did the binning.)

  2. The data set already contains the final counts and we just need to toss up bars of that size. We accomplish this with the geom geom_col() OR geom_bar(stat="identity"). The added argument stat="identity" means "don’t do a _statistical transformation, just use the data as is". In fact, when stat="identity" is not supplied, geom_bar() automatically has stat="count" specified..to count! Check out the documentation of this function for more details.

In our case, we are in scenario #1: There is NO existing column that already has counted the number of species for us, so we will use regular geom_bar(). In a bar plot, the variable of interest (Species) is on the X-axis, and its counts are on the Y-axis.

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species)) + 
  geom_bar()

We see this dataset is very balanced - there are 50 of each species!

Again, we can pretty it up (magenta for demo purposes ONLY. functionally, it just adds unnecessary visual noise).

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Species)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill = Species), color = "magenta") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("skyblue", "blue", "navyblue")) + 
  theme_bw() + # a whole other theme!
  labs(x = "Species",
       y = "Count")

Visualizing relationships with scatterplots

Finally, we can look at the relationship between two variables using scatterplots. Let’s start with plotting Sepal Lengths against Sepal Widths. In general, when we say plot A against B, B goes on the X-axis. So it’s really plot Y against X!!!

In this case, we know some of our aesthetics already: Sepal.Length values will get mapped to the Y-axis, and Sepal.Width values will get mapped to the X-axis. We also know that the geometric shape to use is points, which we can achieve with geom_point().

A basic scatterplot, then, will be made like this:

ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length)) + 
  geom_point()
